    <h1>
      THE FORTUNES OF THE COLVILLE FAMILY.
    </h1>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0001" id="link2HCH0001"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER I.&mdash;THE TWO PICTURES.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">&ldquo;A</span> Merry Christmas,
      and a Happy New Year!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Words, of course, in themselves good and well-chosen, and embodying a wish
      which all who love their neighbour should feel and communicate;&mdash;God
      in his mercy grant there may be very many who can respond to such a
      salutation hopefully; for in this Valley of the Shadow of Death there must
      be some who shrink from it as from a bitter mockery. Of such are those
      who, loving deeply, have lost, or fear to lose, the object of their fond
      idolatry; of such are those to whom, gifted, perhaps, with an even wider
      capacity of affection, such a fear would seem a blessing, for then they
      would not have toiled through a lifetime lonely-hearted. &ldquo;A Merry
      Christmas, and a Happy New Year!&rdquo; God comfort those who shudder at such
      kindly greeting!
    </p>
    <p>
      One short month since, a little space of time, but more than long enough
      for the performance of many a deeper tragedy than that to which we are
      about to refer, an artist, glancing into the sunny breakfast-parlour of
      Ashburn Rectory, might have made a pretty picture of the group on which
      his eye would have fallen.
    </p>
    <p>
      That <i>gentleman</i> (in rags he would equally have looked such) with the
      calm, high forehead, mild eye, and earnest, thoughtful mouth, must be the
      father of the family; for his dark hair shows many a silver thread, and
      the lines that appear upon his still smooth brow can scarcely be the
      result of mental occupation only; but, if we are right in our conjecture,
      whence did that curly-pated nine-year-old urchin, seated upon his knee,
      contrive to get his arch, merry face? for he can scarcely have &ldquo;come
      alive&rdquo; out of one of Murillo&rsquo;s paintings, to give light and life to our
      family sketch. Oh! we see, it is his mother&rsquo;s countenance the rogue has
      appropriated, only the mischief in it is all his own; for the expression
      of her still-beautiful features is chastened and pensive, as of one who
      has lived and loved, and done angels&rsquo; work on earth, until the pure soul
      within has stamped its impress on the outward form.
    </p>
    <p>
      But if you want something pretty&mdash;nay, we may as well tell the whole
      truth, and say at once bewitching&mdash;to look at, cast your eyes (you
      won&rsquo;t be in a hurry to remove them again) upon the figure seated at
      mamma&rsquo;s right hand, and recognising her facsimile (with twenty summers
      taken off her age, and barely eighteen left), declare whether that is not
      &ldquo;nice,&rdquo; rather. The expression is not the same, we confess: more of the
      woman and less of the angel, you will say. We admit it; but then, how
      could that little rosebud of a mouth look anything but petulant? those
      violet eyes express&mdash;well, it&rsquo;s difficult to tell what they don&rsquo;t
      express that is good, and fresh, and piquant, and gay, and&mdash;must we
      add? a little bit coquettish also;&mdash;why, the very dimple on her chin&mdash;such
      a well-modelled chin&mdash;has something pert and saucy about it. There!
      you&rsquo;ve seen enough of the little beauty: you&rsquo;ll be falling in love with
      her directly!
    </p>
    <p>
      No one could mistake the relationship existing between the gentleman we
      have already described, and that tall, graceful boy, with his pale,
      finely-chiselled features, and classically-shaped head. Even the earnest,
      thoughtful expression is common to both father and son, save that the curl
      of the short upper lip, which tells of pride in the boy, has, in the man,
      acquired a character of chastened dignity.
    </p>
    <p>
      Reader, do you like our picture? Let us turn to another, less pleasing,
      but alas! equally true.
    </p>
    <p>
      The waves of time roll on, and, like a dream, another month has lapsed
      into the sea of ages.
    </p>
    <p>
      The sun is shining still; but it shines upon an open grave, with aching
      hearts around it. A good man has died, and his brave, loving spirit has
      gone whither his faith has preceded him, and his good works alone can
      follow him. &ldquo;Blessed are the dead that die in the Lord.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Let us reserve our sympathy for those who live to mourn them.
    </p>
    <p>
      When the curate of Ashburn preached a funeral sermon, recalling to the
      minds of those who had practically benefited by them the virtues of their
      late rector, holly garlands hung in the fine old church, to commemorate
      the birth-time of One who came to bring &ldquo;peace on earth, and good-will
      towards men;&rdquo; but none dared to wish the widow and orphans &ldquo;A Merry
      Christmas, and a Happy New Year,&rdquo; lest the wish might seem an insult to
      their sorrow.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0002" id="link2HCH0002"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER II.&mdash;THE BROTHERS.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">&ldquo;P</span>ercy, I <i>have</i>
      been quiet <i>so</i> long, and you say I must not stand upon my head,
      because it disturbs mamma; do come out and let us ride the pony by turns,&rdquo;
       implored little Hugh Colville in a strenuous whisper; which was, however,
      clearly audible throughout the small breakfast-parlour, which was the
      scene of our family picture.
    </p>
    <p>
      Percy Colville, the shy, handsome boy of our sketch, looked up with a
      pensive smile from the writing on which he was engaged, and shook his head
      negatively, in token that he felt obliged to refuse the request of his
      younger brother, in whom the reader will recognise, with little
      difficulty, a certain Murillo-like urchin to whom he has been already
      introduced. But the petition of her youngest born had reached the ears of
      the widow, who (if she had a virtue which had outgrown its due proportions
      till cavillers might deem it a fault), was, perhaps, a little over
      indulgent to Master Hugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My dear Percy, you have been writing for me long enough,&rdquo; she said, &ldquo;you
      will be ill if you shut yourself up too much; besides, Hugh has been so
      good that he deserves his ride, and you know I don&rsquo;t like to trust him by
      himself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Percy hesitated: the writing on which he was engaged was the copy of a
      surveyor&rsquo;s report concerning that <i>vexata quaestic</i>, dilapidations.
      Some difference of opinion had arisen on this subject between the agent of
      the patron of the living and Mrs. Colville&rsquo;s solicitor, and a copy of the
      report was to be forwarded by the next post to Mr. Wakefield, Mrs.
      Calville&rsquo;s legal adviser. The matter was of importance, involving a
      considerable sum of money. Percy was aware of these facts: he knew, also,
      that he could only just finish his task by the time the village post went
      out; and he was about to declare that Hugh must give up his ride for that
      day, when his mother, reading his thoughts-, stooped over him, and,
      kissing his pale brow, whispered&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do not refuse him, dear Percy: remember, he will not have many more rides&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She paused, for her composure was failing, then finished in a trembling
      voice&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You know the pony must be sold when we go away.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      As she spoke, an expedient suggested itself to Percy&rsquo;s mind, and pressing
      his mother&rsquo;s hand affectionately, he closed his writing-desk, and,
      carrying it off under his arm, exclaimed&mdash;&ldquo;Come along, Hugh! we&rsquo;ll
      take old Lion (he wants a run, poor dog) as well as the pony, and have a
      glorious scamper.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      And a glorious scamper they had, only Hugh rode the whole way, and Percy
      ran by his side, declaring that he greatly preferred it, which was
      decidedly a pious fiction, if a fiction can ever be pious.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh! mamma, mamma! do make breakfast&mdash;come, quick! there&rsquo;s a good
      mamma! for I&rsquo;m as hungry as&mdash;as&mdash;several sharks,&rdquo; exclaimed
      Hugh, rushing like a small express train into the breakfast-parlour, on
      the following morning.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, you naughty mad-cap, you&rsquo;ve shaken the table, and made me blot &lsquo;That
      Smile&rsquo; all over!&rdquo; cried his sister Emily, in vain endeavouring to repair
      the misfortune which had accrued to the &ldquo;popular melody&rdquo; she was copying.
    </p>
    <p>
      We suppose it is scarcely necessary to reintroduce you to Emily, dear
      reader. You have not so soon forgotten the rosebud of a mouth, or the
      dangerous dimple&mdash;trust you for that.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, I declare, so I have,&rdquo; rejoined the culprit, a little shocked and a
      good deal amused at the mischief he had occasioned; then striking into the
      tune of the outraged ditty, he sang in an impish soprano, and with
      grimaces wonderful to behold&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      &ldquo;&lsquo;That smile&mdash;when once&mdash;de-par-ar-ar-arted,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Must leave&mdash;me bro&mdash;ken har-ar-ir-arted.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh! Emily, what a mess we have made of &lsquo;broken-hearted,&rsquo; to be sure I&rsquo;m
      so sorry, but what fun!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      And then came a burst of ringing, happy, childish laughter, which, of
      course, sealed his forgiveness: no one could think him to blame after <i>that</i>.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wonder where Percy is; I scarcely ever knew him late before,&rdquo; observed
      Mrs. Colville, when quiet had been restored.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sarah tells me he is out riding,&rdquo; returned Emily, applying herself with
      very unnecessary energy to cut bread and butter.
    </p>
    <p>
      As she spoke, the clatter of horses&rsquo; feet became audible, and, in another
      moment, Percy cantered past the window.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Where can the boy have been?&rdquo; ejaculated Emily, holding the loaf
      lovingly, as though she was afraid of hurting the poor thing.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I know, I do!&rdquo; observed Hugh, from under the table, whence, having in his
      mind&rsquo;s eye metamorphosed himself into a wolf, he was preparing to spring
      out and devour Emily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>You</i> know, Hugh!&rdquo; repeated Mrs. Colville in surprise; &ldquo;come from
      under the table, then, and tell me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But, mamma, I&rsquo;m a wolf, and just going to eat up Emily.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Not now, dear,&rdquo; was the calm reply, as if a daughter more or less
      devoured by wild beasts was of little moment to that un-anxious mother;
      &ldquo;come here, and tell me about Percy.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, you know, mamma,&rdquo; began Hugh, emerging from his hiding-place, and
      assuming the grave air of a <i>raconteur</i>, &ldquo;when Percy came to bed last
      night, he did not go to bed at all&mdash;that is, not for a very, very,
      very long time. Do you know, I think&rdquo;&mdash;and here he put on a solemn
      face, and spoke with an air of mystery&mdash;&ldquo;I think he was not in bed at
      twelve o&rsquo;clock, perhaps not till almost one!&rdquo; Having disclosed this
      frightful fact, he paused and nodded like a bird, for the greater effect,
      ere he continued: &ldquo;I went to sleep long before, but, whenever I opened my
      eyes, there he sat, still write, write, writing on, as if he was writing
      his life, like Robinson Crusoe&mdash;only,&rdquo; he added, parenthetically&mdash;&ldquo;only
      he&rsquo;s got no man Friday.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But what could he be writing?&rdquo; exclaimed Emily, coquetting with the large
      bread-knife.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I know,&rdquo; resumed Hugh; then, having paused to balance himself on one leg,
      and spin round like a teetotum, he continued very fast, and without any
      stops, for Percy&rsquo;s footsteps sounded in the hall: &ldquo;he was writing the
      paper he had not time to finish yesterday, because I wanted him to go out
      with me and the pony; and this morning he got up at six o&rsquo;clock to ride
      over to Staplehurst, seven miles there, and I don&rsquo;t know how many back
      again, to catch the post, and make it all the same as if it had been put
      in yesterday; I know he did, because Sarah says so.&rdquo; And, having delivered
      himself with the greatest vehemence of this somewhat incoherent account,
      he rushed up to his brother, then entering the room, and, throwing his arm
      as round his waist, exclaimed, &ldquo;Oh, Percy! I&rsquo;ve gone and told them all
      about your great letter, and sitting up late, and everything, and never
      remembered till now that you said I wasn&rsquo;t to mention it to anybody. Oh, I
      am so sorry, but what fun!&rdquo; and, assured by the expression of Percy&rsquo;s face
      that his crime was not quite unpardonable, Hugh&rsquo;s merry, childish laugh
      again rang through the apartment.
    </p>
    <p>
      The mother&rsquo;s heart was full: tears stood in her eyes as, pressing her
      elder son to her bosom, she murmured,&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Dear, dear Percy, you must not overtask your strength thus.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The post that morning brought the following letter directed to Mrs.
      Colville:&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My dear Sister,&mdash;That I have the will to aid you in your distress
      you cannot doubt; that the power to do so effectually is denied me, adds
      one more to the troubles of life. My imprudent marriage (he had run away
      with a pretty governess at eighteen), and its subsequent consequences (he
      had nine healthy children), force me to work like a horse in a mill, in
      order to make both ends meet. Of this I am not complaining.. I did an
      unwise thing, and must pay the necessary penalty. But I mention these
      facts to prove to you the truth of my assertion, that my power is not
      coequal with my will. The little I can do is this: I am shareholder in an
      excellent proprietary school, where boys are taught everything necessary
      to fit them for a commercial life; Wilfred Jacob has been there two years,
      and is already conversant with, or, as he familiarly terms it, &lsquo;well up
      in&rsquo; tare and tret. I trust Adolphus Samuel, Albert John, Thomas Gabriel,
      and even the little Augustus Timothy, will soon follow, and profit
      equally. I therefore propose to send your two boys to this school at my
      own cost; and, if the eldest distinguishes himself, as I am proud to
      believe Wilfred Jacob will do, a desk in my counting-house (No. 8,
      Grubbinger Street, City) shall reward his diligence. Clementina Jane
      desires her kindest regards, and begs me to say that, should you finally
      determine upon settling in London, she shall have much pleasure in looking
      out a cheap lodging for you in some of the least expensive streets in the
      vicinity of Smithfield. I am, dear Margaret, ever your affectionate
      brother,
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Goldsmith and Thryft.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;P.S.&mdash;So much for habit: I have become so accustomed to sign for the
      firm, that I actually forget that my name is Tobiah.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Colville closed the letter, with a sigh, and placing it in her
      pocket, waited till the boys had breakfasted. As soon as they had quitted
      the room she handed it to her daughter, saving. &ldquo;Read that, dear Emily: it
      is very kind of your uncle, but&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Percy at a desk in Grubbinger Street! Oh, my dearest mamma, what a
      dreadful idea!&rdquo; exclaimed the Rosebud, arching her brows, and pursing up
      her pretty little mouth with an expression of the most intense
      disapproval: &ldquo;Uncle Tobiah means to be very kind, but he forgets what
      Percy is.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Colville shook her head mournfully. &ldquo;I am afraid it is we who forget,
      love,&rdquo; she said: &ldquo;Percy can no longer hope to pursue the career marked out
      for him&mdash;with the very limited means at my disposal, college is quite
      out of the question; nay, if Sir Thomas Crawley persists in his demand for
      the incoming tenant&rsquo;s claim to these dilapidations, and should prove his
      right to it, I shall be unable to send the boys to school at all; indeed,
      I must not reject your uncle&rsquo;s offer rashly. I shall consult Mr. Slowkopf
      on the subject; he is a very prudent adviser.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh! if you mean to ask <i>him</i>, the matter is as good as settled, and
      poor Percy chained to a desk for life,&rdquo; cried Emily. &ldquo;Ah!&rdquo; she continued,
      as a tall, thin, gaunt figure, clothed in rusty black, passed the window,
      &ldquo;here he comes&mdash;the creature always puts me in mind of that naughty
      proverb about a certain person: one no sooner mentions him than there he
      is at one&rsquo;s elbow;&mdash;but, if you really want to talk sense to him,
      mamma dear, I&rsquo;d better go, for I shall only say pert things and disturb
      you: he is so delightfully slow and matter-of-fact, that I never can
      resist the temptation of plaguing him;&rdquo; and as she spoke, the Rosebud
      laughed a little silvery laugh at her own wickedness, and tripped,
      fairy-like, out of the apartment.
    </p>
    <p>
      The worthy Mr. Slowkopf, who had held the office of curate of Ashburn for
      about two years, was a very good young man, and nothing else; all his
      other qualities were negative. He wasn&rsquo;t even positively a fool, though he
      looked and acted the part admirably. He was essentially, and in every
      sense of the word, a slow man: in manners, ideas, and appearance, he was
      behind the age in which he lived; in conversation he was behind the
      subject discussed; if he laughed at a joke, which, solemnly and heavily,
      he sometimes condescended to do, it was invariably ten minutes after it
      had been made. He never heard of Puseyism till Tract Ninety had been
      suppressed, or knew of the persecutions and imprisonments of Dr. Achilli
      till that amateur martyr was crying aloud for sympathy in Exeter Hall; he
      usually finished his fish when the cheese was being put on table; and went
      to bed as other people were getting up. Still, he had his good points.
      Unlike King Charles, of naughty memory,
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      &ldquo;Who never said a foolish thing,
    </p>
    <p class="indent20">
      And never did a wise one,&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      however dull and trite might be Mr. Slowkopf&rsquo;s remarks, his actions were
      invariably good and kind. The village gossips, when they were very hard-up
      for scandal, declared that, insensible as he appeared to all such
      frivolities as the fascinations of the softer sex, he was gradually taking
      a &ldquo;slow turn&rdquo; towards the Rosebud of Ashburn. Nay, the rumour was reported
      to have reached the delicate ears of the &ldquo;emphatic she&rdquo; herself; who was
      said to have replied, that as she was quite certain he would never dream
      of telling his love till he heard she was engaged to be married to some
      one else&mdash;in which case she should have a legitimate reason for
      refusing him&mdash;the information did not occasion her the slightest
      uneasiness.
    </p>
    <p>
      However this might be, certain it is, that on the morning in question, Mr.
      Slowkopf, gaunt, ugly, and awkward, solemnly walked into the
      breakfast-parlour, and that the widow, perplexed between her good sense
      and her loving tenderness for her children, laid before him her
      difficulties and her brother&rsquo;s letter.
    </p>
    <p>
      The curate paused about three times as long as was necessary, and then, in
      a deep, sepulchral voice, observed&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In order to attain to a sound and logical conclusion in regard to this
      weighty matter, it behoves me first to assure myself that I rightly
      comprehend the question propounded, and if, as I conceive, it prove to be
      one which will not admit of demonstration with a mathematical certainty;
      then, secondly, so to compare the different hypotheses which may present
      themselves, that, sufficient weight being allotted to each, a just and
      philosophical decision may be finally arrived at.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Having, after this preamble, stated the case in language as precise and
      carefully selected as though he were framing a bill to lay before
      Parliament, and were resolved to guard against <i>the</i> possibility of
      the most astute legal Jehu driving a coach and four through it, he argued
      the matter learnedly and steadily for a good half-hour, ere he dug out the
      ore of common sense from the mass of logical rubbish beneath which he had
      buried it, and decided in favour of Mr. Goldsmith&rsquo;s proposal. Pleased at
      his own cleverness in having solved this difficult problem, and possessing
      unlimited confidence in his oratorical powers, he volunteered to
      communicate the decision thus formed to the person most nearly concerned
      therein, an offer to which Mrs. Colville, feeling her strength unequal to
      the task, reluctantly consented.
    </p>
    <p>
      Percy listened in silence till Mr. Slowkopf had talked himself out of
      breath, which it took him some time to accomplish, for, in every sense of
      the term, he was awfully long-winded; when at length he was silent, the
      boy fixed his large eyes earnestly upon his face as he replied, &ldquo;I
      understand, sir, we are so poor that it is not possible to send me to a
      public school, or to college as&mdash;as&mdash;my dear father wished; but
      I do not see why I am necessarily obliged to become a merchant&rsquo;s clerk, a
      position which I shall never be fit for, and which I hate the idea of; the
      Colvilles have always been gentlemen.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A man may work for his living in some honest occupation without
      forfeiting that title,&rdquo; returned Mr. Slowkopf, sententiously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Not as a merchant&rsquo;s clerk,&rdquo; was the haughty reply: &ldquo;No; let me be an
      artist, if I cannot receive a gentleman&rsquo;s education in England. I know I
      have some talent for drawing, let me study that, and then go to Italy,
      beautiful Italy, for a few years; people can live very cheaply abroad, and
      I will be very careful. When I become famous I shall grow rich, and be
      able to support mamma, and send Hugh to college, and then I shall care
      less for not having been there myself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Without attempting to regard your scheme in its many complicated
      bearings, or to argue the matter in its entire completeness, for which
      time, unfortunately, is wanting,&rdquo; remarked Mr. Slowkopf, deliberately; &ldquo;I
      will place before you, <i>in limine</i>, certain objections to it which
      render the commercial career proposed by your excellent uncle, if not in
      every point a more advantageous arrangement, at all events one more suited
      to the present position of affairs. Your uncle proposes to take upon
      himself all immediate expense connected with your education; while, as a
      clerk in his counting-house, you will be in the receipt of a gradually
      increasing salary. Your scheme would demand a constant outlay of capital,
      for certainly the next five years; nay, it would be no matter of surprise
      to me if ten years should elapse, ere, by the precarious earnings of an
      artist&rsquo;s career, you were enabled to render yourself independent. In one
      case you will be an assistance to your excellent mother, in the other a
      burden upon her.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Percy walked to the window; the burning tears of disappointed ambition and
      mortified pride rushed to his eyes, but he brushed them hurriedly away, as
      he said in a firm, steady voice, &ldquo;Thank you for telling me the truth, Mr.
      Slowkopf; we will accept my uncle&rsquo;s offer.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Thus it came about that Percy and Hugh Colville were entered, as boarders,
      at Doctor Donkiestir&rsquo;s excellent proprietary establishment.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
