      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER VII.&mdash;TEMPTATION.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">&ldquo;C</span>ome here,
      Colville. How is your cat this morning?&rdquo; inquired Norman, as Hugh
      approached, a good deal puzzled, and rather alarmed, at his summons, by
      reason of the fact that when a sixth-form boy sent for one of the little
      fellows, the interview, however it might begin, generally ended by the
      juvenile coming in for a thrashing.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Thank you, sir, she is very well,&rdquo; replied Hugh; then, judging from
      Norman&rsquo;s face that no very adverse fate awaited him, he continued, &ldquo;If you
      please, sir, she caught a rat to-day all her own self; such a monster,
      sir.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Indeed! she must be a most meritorious and praiseworthy animal,&rdquo; returned
      Norman; then, anxious to set the little fellow at his ease before he began
      to pump him, he continued&mdash;&ldquo;How did you like the play yesterday? were
      you very much charmed?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I did not go, if you please, sir.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ha! how was that? Did the Doctor keep you in for a punishment, or don&rsquo;t
      you care about such things?&rdquo; inquired Norman, pretty well foreseeing the
      answer.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, it was not that, sir,&rdquo; returned Hugh. &ldquo;I should have been delighted
      to go; but I had spent all my pocket money, and so could not pay for
      entrance.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Unlucky for you&mdash;very,&rdquo; rejoined Norman; &ldquo;I wish I&rsquo;d known it
      &lsquo;sooner, I&rsquo;d have tipped you the half-crown; more particularly as I want
      you to do something for me. You know the loft well?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hugh grinned, as he replied, &ldquo;Every inch of it, sir.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So used I when I was your age. Is not there a little square window, or
      trap door, by which one can get on the top of the school-room, near the
      part of the skylight which opens? and which can be reached by standing on
      the doctor&rsquo;s desk?&rdquo; inquired Norman.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, sir,&rdquo; was the reply; &ldquo;I often get up that way if the boys are
      plaguing me; and they don&rsquo;t dare to follow me because it is dark inside
      that part of the loft, and they are afraid of a ghost; but I&rsquo;m sure
      there&rsquo;s no ghost, or else Puss would not leave her kittens there: if the
      kittens are safe, why should not I be?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Norman smiled at this specimen of juvenile logic
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That&rsquo;s right,&rdquo; he said, stroking Hugh&rsquo;s curly pate, &ldquo;you&rsquo;re plucky little
      fellow; and now show me this window. I want to see if I have forgotten the
      way.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll show it to you, and willingly, sir,&rdquo; returned Hugh, whose affections
      were easily won, more especially when one of the sixth condescended to lay
      siege to them; &ldquo;but you won&rsquo;t be able to get through yourself, now. You
      were a little fellow&rsquo; like me, I suppose, when you used to do so.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      This information was what the immortal Dick Swiveller would have termed &ldquo;a
      staggerer,&rdquo; and for a moment, Norman began to fear his scheme was knocked
      on the head; but possessing two main elements of greatness, namely&mdash;presence
      of mind and fertility of resource, an alternative occurred to him, which,
      although by no means so safe or easy as his original plan, might yet be
      practicable. Everything depended on the character of the child before him:
      of its strong points he had already some experience, and felt satisfied
      that he might rely on them. The boy possessed pluck enough for his
      purpose: he had now to test his weakness.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Suppose,&rdquo; he begun&mdash;&ldquo;mind, I only say suppose&mdash;there were yet a
      chance of your going to the theatre, what should you think of it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Think! why I should be ready to jump out of my skin for joy, to be sure!&rdquo;
       returned Hugh, his eyes sparkling, and his cheeks flushing at the bare
      idea.
    </p>
    <p>
      Norman had gained a step: he perceived the strength of the temptation he
      had to offer.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well,&rdquo; he said, after keeping Hugh in an agony of expectation for a
      minute or two, &ldquo;there <i>is</i> a chance; but it must depend on whether
      you do exactly as I wish and approve. In the first place, promise me not
      to say a word to anybody about this conversation, or even mention that I
      have been talking to you;&mdash;in the second place, come to me in
      Biggington&rsquo;s room, as soon as dinner is over.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Please, sir, may not I tell Percy? I always tell him everything,&rdquo; pleaded
      Hugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Did you tell him who broke the Doctor&rsquo;s inkglass?&rdquo; inquired Norman,
      sarcastically.
    </p>
    <p>
      Now this inquiry referred to a little affair which had occurred within a
      week of Hugh&rsquo;s first arrival at school. Indulging in what propensity
      common alike to boys and monkeys, viz., of examining everything with their
      fingers&rsquo; ends, Hugh had allowed to fall, and thus broken, Dr. Donkiestir&rsquo;s
      own peculiar inkglass. Overwhelmed with the awful nature of the offence he
      had committed, and expecting, at the very least, to be flogged for the
      same, the poor child sat down by the side of the devastation he had
      caused, and commenced the uncomfortable operation of crying his-eyes out.
    </p>
    <p>
      In this forlorn condition he was discovered by Norman, who, without being
      really kind-hearted, possessed that not uncommon species of negatively
      selfish good-nature, which leads people to dislike to look on distress,
      physical or mental. Moreover, the fact of Hugh being a very pretty boy
      pleased his taste; and therefore interested him. Accordingly, he first
      inquired the cause of his grief, and then devised a remedy.
    </p>
    <p>
      It so happened that Norman&rsquo;s own inkbottle and the one which Hugh had just
      broken, were, as nearly as possible, similar. He knew, moreover, that the
      Doctor was by no means observant of such minor particulars. He,
      accordingly, substituted his bottle for the broken one, assisted Hugh to
      clear away all traces of the accident, and, advising him to keep his own
      counsel, left him greatly consoled. But Hugh felt a consciousness that
      there was something in this transaction of which Percy would not approve;
      and, fearful lest, in his strict sense of honour, he should pronounce it
      necessary to acquaint the Doctor with his delinquency, his moral courage
      failed him, and, up to the moment in which Norman asked him the question,
      he had never revealed the misdeed to his brother. It was the first time he
      had ever been guilty of that mildest form of lying&mdash;suppression of
      the truth; but the stone of dissimulation, once set rolling, soon gathers
      force, which the feeble hand that sufficed to put it in motion is
      powerless to restrain.
    </p>
    <p>
      Nor was Hugh&rsquo;s first &ldquo;little sin&rdquo; fated to prove an exception to the rule.
      Of course he was obliged to confess to Norman that he had not told his
      brother, and of course Norman replied that what he had done once he could
      do again: and that if he cared to go to the play, he must not tell Percy
      or any one; and Hugh, not having a word to say in denial, the discussion
      ended by his promising to preserve a strict silence on the subject, and to
      come to Norman in Biggington&rsquo;s room.
    </p>
    <p>
      In that same apartment was assembled, that afternoon, a solemn conclave.
      Biggington took <i>the</i> chair (there was but one); Stradwick drew a box
      from under the bed, and seated himself upon it, in an attitude exactly
      copied from that of Biggington.
    </p>
    <p>
      Norman, resting his elbow on the chimney-piece, remained standing; while
      Terry turned a wash-hand basin topsy-turvy, and perched himself,
      monkey-like, on the apex of the semi-cone thus created. After a moment&rsquo;s
      silence, Biggington exclaimed&mdash;&ldquo;Well, Norman, how are we going on?
      have you brought your plan to perfection yet?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Unforeseen difficulties have sprung up,&rdquo; was the reply, &ldquo;but none which
      the three Ps&mdash;patience, perseverance, and pluck&mdash;will not carry
      us through.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Difficulties be hanged!&rdquo; rejoined Biggington, impetuously. &ldquo;I tell you
      one thing, go <i>I will</i>, by fair means or foul; the fact is,
      Trevanion&rdquo; (&ldquo;Jack Spratty,&rdquo; murmured Norman. &ldquo;With a great pair of dyed
      moustachios on him,&rdquo; urged Terry) &ldquo;has been here, and promised to take us
      behind the scenes, and to come and sup with us at the Bull afterwards, and
      induce Coralie and the other girl to come too.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ay! and Coralie&rsquo;s a stunner, and no mistake,&rdquo; observed Terry; &ldquo;such a
      pair of black eyes, by Jove! they go through a fellow like&mdash;like&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Bradawls,&rdquo; suggested Stradwick, complacently.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;A <i>pointed</i> illustration, decidedly,&rdquo; resumed Terry; &ldquo;but I was
      walking the day before yesterday with old Beaugentil, when we met this
      said Coralie, taking a constitutional for the benefit of her complexion;
      the moment Beaugentil set eyes upon her, he went off into an ecstacy,
      throwing up his arms and capering about like a bear on hot bricks. &lsquo;<i>Mais,
      ce n&rsquo;est pas possible!</i>&rsquo; he exclaimed, &lsquo;vot shall I be &rsquo;old? <i>Est-ce
      toi, Coralie?</i> Am it thou, Coreliar, zie daugtaire of thy mama, zie
      beloafed <i>de ma premiere jeunesse! et quelle ange!</i> vot an angle! <i>vrai
      ange du ciel</i>, a right angle of &rsquo;eaven! <i>Voyez donc, Monsieur
      Terrie; permettez que je vous présente mon cher élève, Monsieur Terrie,
      june homme charmant; mais n&rsquo;est-ce pas que Mademoiselle est jolie</i>; ees
      not Mees superbe, beautifu, <i>magnifique</i>, pretty vell!&rsquo; and so the
      old boy ran on till I was in fits.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What is your confounded difficulty, Norman?&rdquo; inquired Biggington,
      abruptly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, the window in the loft turns out to be too small for anything bigger
      than a boy to get through,&rdquo; was the reply.
    </p>
    <p>
      Biggington muttered something unintelligible, which it would be the height
      of charity to consider a good word, as he continued&mdash;&ldquo;What do you
      mean to do, then?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Put a small boy through it, who shall open the back door into the
      school-room for us, whereby we shall enter and walk up to bed,&rdquo; returned
      Norman, stroking the raven down on his upper lip, where the &ldquo;cavalry
      moustache&rdquo; was just beginning to show itself.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And what chance is there of finding a boy whom you can trust to do such a
      thing?&rdquo; asked Biggington, gloomily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He is already found, or I am much mistaken,&rdquo; was the answer. &ldquo;Moreover,
      properly handled, he&rsquo;ll do the thing well, and <i>con amore</i>; I&rsquo;d
      sooner work with <i>one</i> willing agent than with twenty forced ones.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And his name?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The younger Colville.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Biggington mused. &ldquo;He might do it; but his brother will not allow him,&rdquo; he
      said after a pause.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;His brother will have no voice in the matter, for he will know nothing
      about it,&rdquo; returned Norman; &ldquo;but you shall judge for yourselves, for I
      have appointed the boy to come to me here. Only leave me to talk to him,
      and don&rsquo;t bully or frighten the little fellow, else you will defeat your
      own object. If, when you have seen him, you wish me to persevere with the
      plan, Biggington, stroke your chin thus.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      As Norman raised his hand to indicate the appointed signal, a modest tap
      at the door was audible, and, on the bolt being withdrawn, Hugh made his
      appearance, and, at a sign from Norman, entered. The door was closed and
      fastened by Terry, who resumed his scat on the inverted wash-hand basin,
      with the air of a monarch ascending his throne. Hugh bore the scrutiny to
      which all the plotters, Biggington in particular, subjected him,
      unflinchingly; he looked rather more grave and anxious than was his wont,
      but did not appear intimidated or abashed, though he stood in the awful
      presence of the cock of the school.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Come here, Colville,&rdquo; began Norman; then, as the boy approached, he
      continued, fixing his piercing glance upon him, &ldquo;have you mentioned what
      we were talking about this morning to anybody?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, sir,&rdquo; was the unhesitating reply.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Not to your brother, eyen? don&rsquo;t attempt to deceive me!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, indeed, sir, I would not tell a lie; if I had mentioned it to Percy,
      I&rsquo;d say so at once,&rdquo; returned Hugh, colouring at his assertion being
      doubted.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I believe you,&rdquo; replied Norman, glancing towards Biggington as he spoke
      to attract his attention. &ldquo;I am sure you are a brave, honourable boy, who
      would neither tell a lie nor betray a secret, which is worse, if
      anything.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      At this commendation, Hugh&rsquo;s eyes sparkled, and a bright, honest smile lit
      up his innocent, childish face, which ought to have touched the hearts and
      disarmed the purpose of those who, for their own selfish ends, were thus
      deliberately leading him into evil; it probably would have done so, were
      it not a well-established fact in pathology, that, during the phase of
      public schoolboyhood, the human heart remains in a torpid or chrysalis
      state; the animal, at that period, consisting of a head, a stomach, and
      (fortunately for those who have the control of it, as well for its future
      chance of developing into a reasonable mortal) a tail also. Not being
      actuated by any such tender feelings, or indeed by an feelings at all,
      except selfish ones, Biggington replied to Norman&rsquo;s look by stroking his
      chin. Stradwick stroked his at the same moment, giving involuntarily a
      slight shudder at the alarming future to which he was thus committing
      himself. Terry only grinned, which indeed was his invariable custom on all
      occasions, solemn or comic.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;As I am now convinced that you are trustworthy,&rdquo; resumed Norman, &ldquo;I am
      going to tell you a secret; <i>the</i> secret, in fact, upon the safe
      keeping of which depends your going to the play.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Or getting every bone in your skin broken,&rdquo; muttered Biggington in an
      aside, which was, however, sufficiently audible to convey to Hugh a
      knowledge of the alternative which awaited him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mr. Biggington, these other gentlemen, and myself,&rdquo; continued Norman,
      &ldquo;mean to go to the theatre this evening, and if you will do exactly as we
      tell you, we will take you with us.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But the Doctor!&rdquo; exclaimed Hugh, aghast.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That is the very point I was about to touch upon,&rdquo; rejoined Norman, in no
      way discomposed: &ldquo;the Doctor not approving of the younger boys being out
      at night, thought himself obliged to give a general order to the whole
      school; but at the same time he contrived to have it hinted privately to
      <i>us</i>, that if the elder members of the sixth form chose to go, he
      should not make any inquiries about it; the only point he insisted on
      being, that such an expedition must be managed privately, and without his
      being supposed to know anything about it. Now in order to contrive this,
      we had thought of making our way in at night (we can easily get out
      unobserved after five o&rsquo;clock school), through the window in the loft;
      but, as you say, and as I now remember, it is too small to render that
      possible,&mdash;we want you to get through the sky-light into the
      school-room (as we were talking about this morning), and unfasten the
      little door which opens into the playground; it is only secured by one
      bolt, which is not above your reach, so you can easily undo it. If you
      will undertake this, and promise faithfully not to breathe a word about it
      to anybody, you shall go with us to the play.&rdquo; Poor Hugh was sorely
      puzzled; and his sense of right and wrong entirely confused; one idea,
      however, soon extricating itself from the chaos, he immediately gave it
      utterance. &ldquo;The Doctor,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;will be angry with <i>me</i>, sir,
      though he may not be so with you, for I am only a little fellow, and a
      long way off the sixth form.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Norman hesitated; he knew that if they were discovered he should be quite
      unable to protect the child from punishment, and a sense of self-respect
      made him adverse to pledge himself to anything which he could not perform.
    </p>
    <p>
      Biggington was trammelled by no such scruples. &ldquo;Never fear, young&rsquo;un,&rdquo; he
      said; &ldquo;if the Doctor should by any chance speak to you on the subject,
      just refer, him quietly to me; merely say,&mdash;Biggington desired me to
      go; Biggington will explain everything;&mdash;and you&rsquo;ll have no more
      trouble from the Doctor. Don&rsquo;t you think so, Stradwick?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh! certainly,&rdquo; was the reply: &ldquo;refer him to Biggington, by all means;
      say&mdash;Biggington desired me to go; Biggington will&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That will do,&rdquo; interrupted Terry, grinning. &ldquo;Shut up, Slow-coach, we
      didn&rsquo;t <i>encore</i> the sentiment; moreover, I can perceive by the
      expression of our young friend&rsquo;s optics, that he is awake to a sense of
      his sitiwation. The play, a jolly good supper, and immortal honour and
      renown on one hand; and an awful thrashing from Biggington, with a gentle
      refresher from myself appended, on the other; between such a Scylla and
      Charybdis he will hardly be inclined to forestall Jack Sprattly by
      singing, &lsquo;How happy could I be with either.&rsquo; So now, young&rsquo;un, favour us
      with your sentiments.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If I might but tell Percy!&rdquo; pleaded Hugh, glancing appealingly towards
      Norman.
    </p>
    <p>
      That individual shook his head.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If you do,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;you will have broken the trust reposed in you, and
      proved yourself a mean-spirited, cowardly child, quite unfit for the
      service we require of you, or the pleasure with which we propose to reward
      you;&mdash;tell your brother, and you lose the play.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Poor Hugh! his better nature made one final struggle, but he had dallied
      with the temptation till it had obtained too firm a hold on his
      imagination to be shaken off; and so, like many folks older and wiser than
      himself, who have indulged in a reprehensible longing for some forbidden
      fruit till the appetite has grown too strong to be resisted, he fell.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I <i>will</i> promise,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;I do so want to see the play, and you
      will take care of me if the Doctor is angry, Mr. Biggington?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, decidedly; both myself and Stradwick,&rdquo; was the reply. &ldquo;Stradwick and
      the Doctor are hand and glove just now, because Straddy&rsquo;s such a dab at
      Euripides.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      This insinuation referred to the uncomfortable fact, that the head-master
      had that morning informed Stradwick, in consequence of his total inability
      to construe the works of the ancient Greek in question, that if after
      another week he did not perceive a very decided improvement, he should be
      under the disagreeable necessity of degrading him to the fifth form.
      Stradwick, therefore, hung his head sheepishly as he echoed&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh yes, decidedly.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We understand each other, then, and had better agree to meet here,
      prepared to start, at a quarter to six,&rdquo; observed Norman.
    </p>
    <p>
      A general assent was given, and the conspirators separated. Norman glanced
      at his victim; there was a determined look in the boy&rsquo;s face, which gave
      assurance that he would go through with the task he had undertaken.
      Resolution was one of the few qualities Norman reverenced, and for the
      moment he repented the evil into which he was leading the child; but the
      two strongest passions of his nature, ambition and revenge, were linked
      with his scheme for that evening, and he could not relinquish it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Courage, little one,&rdquo; he said, laying his hand on Hugh&rsquo;s curly pate; &ldquo;if
      you and I live, and, as something here&rdquo;&mdash;and he touched his forehead
      as he spoke&mdash;&ldquo;tells me will be the case, I achieve greatness, I will
      not forget this evening. Silence and courage!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
